
### Iterative Approach

I use a stack to manually store the current state. Each state contains the current combination, the remaining target, and the index from where I should continue choosing candidates. At every step, I pop one state from the stack, check if the remaining target is `0`, and if yes, I add the combination to the result. If the remaining target is still positive, I try adding candidates from the current index onward. Since the same candidate can be reused, I keep the next state’s index as `i` instead of `i + 1`.

---

### Solution

cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> combinationSum(vector<int>& candidates, int target) {
        vector<vector<int>> result;

        stack<pair<vector<int>, pair<int, int>>> st;

        st.push({{}, {target, 0}});

        while (!st.empty()) {
            vector<int> combination = st.top().first;
            int remaining = st.top().second.first;
            int start = st.top().second.second;

            st.pop();

            if (remaining == 0) {
                result.push_back(combination);
                continue;
            }

            if (remaining < 0) {
                continue;
            }

            for (int i = start; i < candidates.size(); i++) {
                vector<int> newCombination = combination;

                newCombination.push_back(candidates[i]);

                st.push({newCombination, {remaining - candidates[i], i}});
            }
        }

        return result;
    }
};


### Complexity

Time Complexity: O(N^(T/M))
Where N is the number of candidates, T is the target, and M is the smallest candidate.

Space Complexity: O(N^(T/M))
Because the stack can store many partial combinations in the worst case.
